40.name: Bernal Hill Park
40.history: Presumably named after José Cornelio Bernal, but may have been named after his grandfather, Anza expedition member Juan Francisco Bernal.

50.name: Candlestick Park
50.history: Named for its location on Candlestick Point, for which the origin of the name is disputed.  One popular theory is that it was named for a nearby rock formation in the Bay that resembled a candlestick.

80.name: Crissy Field
80.history: Originally the site of a US Army airfield named in honor of Major Dana H. Crissy, who was killed in a plane crash in Salt Lake City in 1919.

90.name: De Young Museum
90.history: Originated as the Fine Arts Building for the California Midwinter International Exposition in 1894.  The museum was renamed in honor of San Francisco Chronicle co-founder Michael H. de Young after his contributions to the construction of a new building completed in 1919.

140.name: Kezar Stadium
140.history: Named for Mary Kezar, who donated $100,000 to the San Francisco Park Commission.  Home stadium to the San Francisco 49ers from 1946 to 1970 and the Oakland Raiders for part of the 1960 season.

150.name: Legion of Honor
150.history: Named after the Palais de la Légion d'Honneur in Paris, the seat and museum of the Legion of Honour, the highest order of French chivalry.  The California Palace of the Legion of Honor is a three-quarter-scale reproduction of the Parisian version.  It was donated by San Francisco sugar magnate Adolph Spreckels and his wife Alma de Bretteville Spreckels and completed in 1924.

160.name: Mark Hopkins Hotel
160.history: The hotel is built on the site of Mark Hopkins' former mansion, which burned down in the fires following the 1906 earthquake.

210.name: Stern Grove
210.history: The site for Stern Grove was donated in 1931 by Rosalie Meyer Stern, widow of the philanthropist Sigmund Stern.

230.name: UC Hastings
230.history: Former California Chief Justice Serranus Clinton Hastings endowed the school with $100,000 in 1878 and also served as dean.  His donation stipulated that the school had to remain in San Francisco, and unlike the rest of the University of California system, could not be governed by the Regents of the University of California.  As a result, the school's dean obtains funds directly from the California State Legislature instead of the Regents.

240.name: Union Square
240.history: Created as a park in 1850 under Mayor John Geary, the square got its current name because it was a prominent location for pro-Union rallies before and during the Civil War.

260.name: Yerba Buena Gardens
260.history: Yerba Buena was the original name for San Francisco under Spanish and later Mexican rule. It was claimed by the United States during the Mexican-American War and renamed to San Francisco by Washington A. Bartlett in 1847. The name Yerba Buena, Spanish for "good herb," refers to a native plant.

470.name: Albion Street
470.history: From the Latin for "white," an archaic term for Great Britain that refers to the White Cliffs of Dover. When Sir Francis Drake landed in California in 1579, he named it Nova Albion ("New Britain").

810.name: Apparel Way
810.history: This street originally ran through Apparel CIty, a large garment trade center opened in 1948.

950.name: Argonaut Avenue
950.history: Settlers during the California Gold Rush were nicknamed "Argonauts" in reference to Jason's mythical quest for the Golden Fleece.

1370.name: Barnard Avenue
1370.history: Likely named after military engineer John G. Barnard.

1750.name: Bernal Heights Boulevard
1750.history: Presumably named after José Cornelio Bernal, but may have been named after his grandfather, Anza expedition member Juan Francisco Bernal.

1940.name: Blake Street
1940.history: Likely named after San Francisco Mayor Maurice Carey Blake.

2010.name: Boardman Place
2010.history: Possibly named after surveyor W.F. Boardman.

2450.name: Buena Vista Avenue East
2450.history: Possibly named for the Battle of Buena Vista, also known as the Battle of Angostura, Zachary Taylor's greatest victory of the Mexican-American War. Helped win Taylor the presidency in 1848.

2460.name: Buena Vista Avenue West
2460.history: Possibly named for the Battle of Buena Vista, also known as the Battle of Angostura, Zachary Taylor's greatest victory of the Mexican-American War. Helped win Taylor the presidency in 1848.

2470.name: Buena Vista Terrace
2470.history: Possibly named for the Battle of Buena Vista, also known as the Battle of Angostura, Zachary Taylor's greatest victory of the Mexican-American War. Helped win Taylor the presidency in 1848.

2780.name: Capp Street
2780.history: Possibly named for Charles A. Capp, a secretary of the San Francisco Real Estate Board in the 19th century.

3350.name: Church Street
3350.history: Presumably named after nearby Mission Dolores.

3610.name: Cole Street
3610.history: Likely named after physician Richard Beverly Cole.

3630.name: Colin P Kelly Jr Street
3630.history: Originally named Japan Street, later renamed to honor American aviator Colin P. Kelly, Jr.

3640.name: College Avenue
3640.history: Located near the former site of St. Mary's College before it moved to Oakland in 1889.

3650.name: College Terrace
3650.history: Located near the former site of St. Mary's College before it moved to Oakland in 1889.

4190.name: Crissy Field Avenue
4190.history: Nearby Crissy Field was originally the site of a US Army airfield named in honor of Major Dana H. Crissy, who was killed in a plane crash in Salt Lake City in 1919.

4400.name: Darien Way
4400.history: Possibly named after either the Isthmus of Darién (now the Isthmus of Panama) or Santa María la Antigua del Darién, the first European settlement in South America, from which Vasco Núñez de Balboa set out for his historic sighting of the Pacific Ocean.

4420.name: Dashiell Hammett Street
4420.history: Formerly known as Monroe Street before being renamed after the author Dashiell Hammett.

4610.name: Delancey Street
4610.history: Named for the Delancey Street Foundation, a San Francisco nonprofit founded in 1971 that offers substance abuse rehabilitation and vocational training.

4780.name: Division Street
4780.history: Presumably named for its location as a boundary between two parts of the street grid.  Streets south of Division Street run directly north-south or east-west, whereas streets north of it run northwest-southeast or northeast-southwest.

4830.name: Donner Avenue
4830.history: Presumably named after the Donner Party, an ill-fated pioneer expedition from Illinois to California that included brothers George and Jacob Donner.  Donner Pass and Donner Lake in the Sierra Nevada mountains are also named for them.

4960.name: Downey Street
4960.history: Possibly named after early California governor John G. Downey.

4970.name: Drake Street
4970.history: Presumably named after explorer Sir Francis Drake.

5080.name: Earl Street
5080.history: Possibly named after John O. Earl, an early San Francisco pioneer and member of the Committee of Vigilance of 1851.

5260.name: Elizabeth Street
5260.history: Named for the wife of John Meirs Horner, an early San Francisco settler responsible for much of the initial development of Noe Valley (the neighborhood was originally known as Horner's Addition).

5370.name: Embarcadero North Street
5370.history: From the Spanish "embarcar" (to embark), the name refers to this boulevard's location along the San Francisco waterfront.

5580.name: Eureka Street
5580.history: The state motto of California, Greek for "I have found it."

5620.name: Ewing Terrace
5620.history: Located on the former site of Ewing Field, briefly the home stadium for the San Francisco Seals and named for the team's owner, James Calvin Ewing.  The Seals, a professional baseball team in the Pacific Coast League, played only the 1914 season at Ewing Field before moving back to their old stadium near the corner of 15th Street & Valencia Street due to the fog and cold weather at the new site.

6180.name: Freelon Street
6180.history: Possibly named after 19th-century magistrate judge T.W. Freelon.

6230.name: Front Street
6230.history: Originally located on the San Francisco waterfront before the city's boundaries were extended with landfill.

6250.name: Funston Avenue
6250.history: This street sits between 12th and 14th Avenues instead of a 13th Avenue, presumably because of superstitions about the unlucky number 13.

6260.name: Funston Road
6260.history: This street sits between 12th and 14th Avenues instead of a 13th Avenue, presumably because of superstitions about the unlucky number 13.

6450.name: Gellert Drive
6450.history: Presumably named after real estate developers Fred and Carl Gellert, who founded the Standard Building Company and built a number of subdivisions in southwestern San Francisco and Daly City during the early 20th century.

6510.name: Germania Street
6510.history: Named for the large contingent of German families originally located in this area.

6540.name: Giants Drive
6540.history: Named for its proximity to Candlestick Park, home stadium of the San Francisco Giants from 1960-1999.

6580.name: Gilroy Street
6580.history: Presumably named after John Gilroy, a Royal Navy sailor, early California settler, and namesake of the California city.

6740.name: Golden Gate Avenue
6740.history: The strait that connects the Pacific Ocean and San Francisco Bay was named the Golden Gate by John C. Fremont in 1846. The name refers to the Golden Horn, the inlet forming the natural harbor of ancient Byzantium (now Istanbul).

6880.name: Grant Avenue
6880.history: Originally named Du Pont Street after naval officer Samuel Du Pont.

7060.name: Haight Street
7060.history: Presumably named after the banker Henry Haight, but this is uncertain. There were two other Haight brothers in San Francisco in the early 1850's, Fletcher and Samuel Haight, and Fletcher's son Henry Huntly Haight went on to become governor of California.

7260.name: Harris Place
7260.history: Presumably named after early San Francisco mayor Stephen Randall Harris.

7270.name: Harrison Boulevard
7270.history: Presumably named after local merchant Edward H. Harrison.

7280.name: Harrison Street
7280.history: Presumably named after local merchant Edward H. Harrison.

7380.name: Hayes Street
7380.history: Presumably named after local businessman Thomas Hayes, but may also refer to his brother Michael and the rest of the Hayes family.

7670.name: Hitchcock Lane
7670.history: Possibly named after film director Alfred Hitchcock, who shot many of his films in and around San Francisco.

7680.name: Hitchcock Street
7680.history: Possibly named after film director Alfred Hitchcock, who shot many of his films in and around San Francisco.

7820.name: Hopkins Avenue
7820.history: Presumably named after railroad magnate Mark Hopkins.

7910.name: Humboldt Street
7910.history: Presumably named after German naturalist and explorer Alexander von Humboldt.

8310.name: Jersey Street
8310.history: Named for the birthplace of John Meirs Horner, an early San Francisco settler responsible for much of the initial development of Noe Valley (the neighborhood was originally known as Horner's Addition).

8410.name: Juan Bautista Circle
8410.history: Presumably named after Spanish explorer Juan Bautista de Anza.

8880.name: Laguna Street
8880.history: Named for Laguna Pequeña, or Washerwoman's Lagoon, a pond in present-day Cow Hollow that was used for washing laundry in the 19th century.

9660.name: Loyola Terrace
9660.history: Named for the founder of the Jesuit order, St. Ignatius of Loyola (this street is located next to the campus of the University of San Francisco, a Jesuit institution).

9730.name: Lurline Street
9730.history: Named for the luxury ocean liner SS Lurline which traveled regularly between San Francisco and Hawaii in the early 20th century.

9850.name: Madison Street
9850.history: Presumably named after President James Madison.

9910.name: Maiden Lane
9910.history: An early center of San Francisco's "red light" district, originally named Morton Street.  It was renamed after the 1906 earthquake, supposedly in honor of the Maiden Lane in New York, a center of that city's jewelry trade at the time.

10460.name: Mendosa Avenue
10460.history: Possibly named after Antonio de Mendoza, the viceroy of New Spain from 1535-1550.

11470.name: Niantic Avenue
11470.history: Named for the whaling vessel Niantic, which brought a large group of goldseekers from New England to San Francisco in 1849. After its arrival, the ship was put aground and converted into a warehouse and hotel. The hull of the Niantic, buried near the current corner of Clay and Sansome Streets, has been repeatedly rediscovered during excavations and construction projects, most recently in 1978.

11760.name: Octavia Street
11760.history: Named by Charles Gough in honor of his sister Octavia.

12010.name: Page Street
12010.history: May have been named for Robert C. Page, a clerk to the San Francisco Board of Aldermen from 1851-1856.

12910.name: Quintara Street
12910.history: Most of the streets parallel to Quintara Street are named alphabetically after figures from the history of Alta California and the Anza expedition, but the name Quintara may have been invented by the Parkside Realty Company.

14010.name: Saint Mary's Avenue
14010.history: Located near the former site of St. Mary's College before it moved to Oakland in 1889.

14610.name: Serrano Drive
14610.history: Likely named after Juan Bautista de Anza's wife, Ana Regina Serrano.

14630.name: Seward Street
14630.history: Likely named after Secretary of State William H. Seward.

15220.name: Steiner Street
15220.history: Likely named after a water deliveryman and friend of Thomas H. Gough (Gough served on the 1855 committee tasked with naming the streets of the Western Addition).

15620.name: Telegraph Hill Boulevard
15620.history: Named for Telegraph Hill, the site of an early telegraph station that displayed semaphore signals announcing which ships were entering San Francisco Bay.

15760.name: Thomas More Way
15760.history: Named for St. Thomas More Church, which is located on this street.

16180.name: Upton Avenue
16180.history: Possibly named for early San Francisco newspaperman Matthias Gilbert Upton.

16190.name: Upton Street
16190.history: Possibly named for early San Francisco newspaperman Matthias Gilbert Upton.

16210.name: Urbano Drive
16210.history: Named for the Urban Realty Improvement Company, which developed the surrounding neighborhood in the early 20th century.  The oval path of the street follows the path of the old Ingleside Racetrack.

16250.name: Valencia Street
16250.history: Most likely named for local landowner Candelario Valencia, but may be named for his father, José Manuel Valencia, a member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

16310.name: Valparaiso Street
16310.history: Named by surveyor Jasper O'Farrell after the city of the same name in Chile, where he lived prior to San Francisco.

16860.name: Wawona Street
16860.history: Most of the streets parallel to Wawona Street are named alphabetically after figures from the history of Alta California and the Anza expedition. The names were selected by the Parkside Realty Company, but the origin of the name Wawona is not clear.

17050.name: Whipple Avenue
17050.history: Likely named after military engineer and surveyor Amiel W. Whipple.

17250.name: Winfield Street
17250.history: Likely named after General Winfield Scott.

17320.name: Woodward Street
17320.history: Robert Woodward owned a large plot of land near 13th Street and Mission Street that he opened to the public from 1866-1894 as the amusement park Woodward's Gardens.  The park included a zoo, roller rink, art gallery, and a Museum of Natural Wonders.

17440.name: Yerba Buena Avenue
17440.history: Yerba Buena was the original name for San Francisco under Spanish and later Mexican rule. It was claimed by the United States during the Mexican-American War and renamed to San Francisco by Washington A. Bartlett in 1847. The name Yerba Buena, Spanish for "good herb," refers to a native plant.

17450.name: Yerba Buena Lane
17450.history: Yerba Buena was the original name for San Francisco under Spanish and later Mexican rule. It was claimed by the United States during the Mexican-American War and renamed to San Francisco by Washington A. Bartlett in 1847. The name Yerba Buena, Spanish for "good herb," refers to a native plant.

17630.name: California Street
17630.history: The name "California" is likely a reference to Garci Rodríguez de Montalvo's popular 16th-century novel Las Sergas de Esplandián, which describes a fictional island paradise named California, inhabited by woman warriors and named for their queen, Calafia.

17690.name: Dewey Boulevard
17690.history: Presumably named after Admiral George Dewey.

18050.name: Sansome Street
18050.history: Likely named after Sansom Street in Philadelphia. The 'e' was not included on early maps of San Francisco, but was added after Jasper O'Farrell's 1847 survey of the city.

18130.name: Vicente Street
18130.history: Presumably named after one of the members of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco who shared the name Vicente.

18160.name: Battery Street
18160.history: Commemorates a fortification erected on Clark's Point in 1847, originally known as Fort Montgomery.

18210.name: Divisadero Street
18210.history: Likely refers to nearby Lone Mountain and the Spanish word for a tall summit, but may instead refer to the fact that this street was once the western boundary of the city, separating it from the Presidio.

18330.name: Mission Street
18330.history: The longest street in San Francisco, named for its path along the original mission trail, which connected Mission Dolores and the village of Yerba Buena.

18530.name: Brotherhood Way
18530.history: Named for the many churches and temples that line the street, including Congregation Beth Israel-Judea, the Holy Trinity Greek Orthodox Church, the Richmond Masonic Temple, and the St. Gregory Armenian Church.

18550.name: Cesar Chavez Street
18550.history: This street was previously named Army Street until it was renamed for Cesar Chavez in 1995.

18560.name: Embarcadero South Street
18560.history: From the Spanish "embarcar" (to embark), the name refers to this boulevard's location along the San Francisco waterfront.

18570.name: Fell Street
18570.history: Likely named after Danish-born pioneer and San Francisco merchant William Fell.

18610.name: Kezar Drive
18610.history: Named for Mary Kezar, who donated $100,000 to the San Francisco Park Commission in 1922 and funded the construction of Kezar Stadium.

18650.name: Market Street
18650.history: The diagonal thoroughfare, created by surveyor Jasper O'Farrell in 1847, was likely named after the Market Street in Philadelphia.

18660.name: Masonic Avenue
18660.history: Named for the Masonic cemetery that was originally to the west of this street, between Fulton and Turk Streets.

18690.name: Octavia Boulevard
18690.history: Named by Charles Gough in honor of his sister Octavia.

18825.name: Golden Gate Bridge
18825.history: The strait that connects the Pacific Ocean and San Francisco Bay was named the Golden Gate by John C. Fremont in 1846. The name refers to the Golden Horn, the inlet forming the natural harbor of ancient Byzantium (now Istanbul).

18840.name: Lombard Street
18840.history: Named after the street of the same name in Philadelphia by San Francisco surveyor Jasper O'Farrell.

18910.name: The Embarcadero
18910.history: From the Spanish "embarcar" (to embark), the name refers to this boulevard's location along the San Francisco waterfront.

1.name: Luis Joaquin Alvarez de Acevedo
1.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

4.name: Joseph S. Alemany
4.desc: Originally born in Catalonia, Alemany was the first Archbishop of San Francisco, serving from 1853-1884.  Prior to that, he served as Bishop of Monterey, making him the first American bishop in California.

5.name: Juan Bautista Alvarado
5.desc: A two-time governor of Alta California and a key figure opposing the American occupation during the Mexican-American War.

6.name: Domingo Alviso
6.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1776 expedition.

7.name: José María Amador
7.desc: A wealthy rancher and administrator of Mission San José (in modern-day Fremont).  Amador was born in the Presidio of San Francisco in 1794.

8.name: Juan Bautista de Anza
8.desc: The leader of the 1775-1776 Spanish expedition to San Francisco, and later Governor of Nuevo México (now the state of New Mexico).

10.name: María Feliciana Arballo
10.desc: Arballo was set to accompany her husband on Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco with her two children. Her husband passed away before the expedition but she chose to join the expedition without him, earning the nickname "The Merry Widow" of California history.

11.name: Ardath Nichols
11.desc: A community leader in Bayview/Hunters Point during the 1960s.  Served as president of the Bayview Neighborhood Center and executive director of the Crispus Attucks Senior Center.

12.name: Manuel Ramirez Arellano
12.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

13.name: José Darío Argüello
13.desc: The governor of Alta California from 1814-1815 and Baja California from 1815-1822, and founder of the pueblo that became the city of Los Angeles.

14.name: Lewis Addison Armistead
14.desc: A US Army captain who left to fight for the Confederacy during the Civil War, during which he was killed in Pickett's Charge at the Battle of Gettysburg.

15.name: Samuel Chapman Armstrong
15.desc: A Union officer in the Civil War who went on to found the Hampton Institute, one of the first post-secondary institutions for blacks in America.  Armstrong was also a key influence on Booker T. Washington, a Hampton student.

16.name: Chester A. Arthur
16.desc: President of the United States from 1881-1885.

17.name: Munroe Ashbury
17.desc: A member of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors for the fifth ward from 1864-1870. Ashbury and Henry Haight were key planners of the Haight-Ashbury neighborhood and nearby Golden Gate Park.

19.name: Adolph Sutro
19.desc: Mayor of San Francisco from 1894-1896.  Sutro was previously a mining engineer who became wealthy through a tunneling operation in the Comstock Lode.

20.name: Edward Dickinson Baker
20.desc: A prominent Illinois lawyer, congressman, and close friend of Abraham Lincoln's who moved to San Francisco in 1852. While practicing in San Francisco, he most famously defended Charles Cora, accused of killing a US Marshal. When the jury failed to reach a verdict, Cora was lynched by a vigilante mob associated with the San Francisco Committee of Vigilance. Baker was also a leader of the movement to keep California in the Union leading up to the Civil War. He organized the 1st California infantry regiment of the Union Army and served as colonel while also serving as a US senator from Oregon, and was killed at the Battle of Ball's Bluff in 1861, the only sitting senator to be killed at war. Baker is buried in the Presidio.

21.name: Vasco Núñez de Balboa
21.desc: Spanish explorer and conquistador who crossed the Isthmus of Panama and became the first European to discover the Pacific Ocean (then called the South Sea) from the New World in 1513.  He was beheaded for treason in 1519.

22.name: James Baldwin
22.desc: An American novelist, playwright, and civil rights activist, author of Notes of a Native Son and Go Tell It on the Mountain.

23.name: Hubert Howe Bancroft
23.desc: A bookseller, collector, and historian, the author of a 39-volume history of the American West. Bancroft sold his 60,000-volume collection to the University of California in 1905, becoming the namesake for the Bancroft Library at UC Berkeley.

24.name: John G. Barnard
24.desc: An engineer for the US and Union armies who constructed batteries and fortifications in San Francisco Bay during the mid-19th century, including Alcatraz and Fort Point.

25.name: Washington A. Bartlett
25.desc: Became the first American alcalde (the equivalent of mayor) of Yerba Buena in 1846, changing its name to San Francisco in 1847.

26.name: Edward F. Beale
26.desc: A naval officer, explorer, frontiersman, and rancher who built a wagon road that later became part of Route 66 and the Transcontinental Railroad. Beale also carried the first California gold samples to the east, helping to spark the California Gold Rush. He was appointed Surveyor General of California and Nevada by President Lincoln in 1861, and purchased Mexican land grants in 1865 to form the 270,000-acre Tejon Ranch, currently the largest private landholding in California.

28.name: Beatrice L. Dunbar
28.desc: A longtime community activist and education advocate in Bayview-Hunters Point, head of the Bayview-Hunters Point Parent Action Group.

29.name: Josiah Belden
29.desc: A member of the first emigrant party to reach California in 1841.  After San Jose became the second incorporated city in California in 1850, Belden served as its first mayor.

30.name: George Berkeley
30.desc: An Irish bishop and philosopher, Berkeley became the namesake of the East Bay city in 1866 when College of California trustee Frederick Billings was inspired by Berkeley's stanza, "Westward the course of empire takes its way; The first four Acts already past, A fifth shall close the Drama with the day; Time's noblest offspring is the last."

32.name: José Cornelio Bernal
32.desc: The recipient of the land grant for Rancho Rincon de las Salinas y Potrero Viejo, which included 4,446 acres of present-day southern San Francisco and northern San Mateo counties. His grandfather, Juan Francisco Bernal, was a member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

33.name: Bertha Freeman
33.desc: A Hunters Point community activist, involved in the early planning of local housing development in the 1960s.

34.name: Nathaniel Blackstone
34.desc: An early local merchant and member of the San Francisco Committee of Vigilance.

35.name: Maurice Carey Blake
35.desc: A local lawyer and member of the California Assembly who served as mayor of San Francisco from 1881-1883.

36.name: Isaac Bluxome
36.desc: A leader of the San Francisco Committee of Vigilance in 1851 and 1856.

37.name: W.F. Boardman
37.desc: Alameda County Surveyor from 1865-1869 and the namesake of Mount Boardman in the Diablo Range (east of present-day San Jose).

38.name: Andrés Bonifacio
38.desc: A Filipino nationalist and revolutionary, leader of the Philippine Revolution in 1896.

39.name: Domingo Alviso
39.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

40.name: Diego de Borica
40.desc: A Spanish explorer and governor of Alta and Baja California from 1794-1800.

41.name: Samuel Brannan
41.desc: Brannan arrived in Yerba Buena in 1846 along with a ship of 245 other Latter Day Saints investigating new possible locations for their center. He went on to found the California Star, the first newspaper in San Francisco, run supply stores for gold miners, and help organize the San Francisco Committee of Vigilance.

42.name: Patrick Breen
42.desc: A Donner Party survivor and author of a diary later published as Diary of the Donner Party.

43.name: Bret Harte
43.desc: An author and chronicler of pioneer life and the California Gold Rush.

44.name: David C. Broderick
44.desc: A member of the California State Senate and San Francisco political boss in the 1850s.  Broderick served as a US Senator from 1857-1859 but was killed in a duel with David S. Terry, former Chief Justice of the California Supreme Court.  He is buried at Lone Mountain Cemetery near the University of San Francisco.

45.name: Horace Brooks
45.desc: The commander of the Presidio from 1872-1877.

46.name: Edwin Bryant
46.desc: A local author and landowner who served as the second American alcalde (the equivalent of mayor) of San Francisco in 1847.

47.name: Antonio María de Bucareli y Ursúa
47.desc: The Viceroy of New Spain during Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco. Bucareli also dispatched two other expeditions to explore the Pacific Northwest.

48.name: John C. Buchanan
48.desc: An early San Francisco auctioneer and politican who served as clerk to alcaldes Edwin Bryant and George Hyde.

50.name: Peter H. Burnett
50.desc: Elected as the first governor of the State of California in 1849, he later served as a justice of the California Supreme Court.

52.name: M.H. de Young
52.desc: The founder of the Daily Dramatic Chronicle newspaper, which went on to become the San Francisco Chronicle. De Young chaired the organizing committee for the 1894 California Midwinter International Exposition and was actively involved in construction of a new home for the Fine Arts Building in the 1910s and 1920s, which was later renamed in his honor.

53.name: Justin Herman
53.desc: Head of the San Francisco Redevelopment Agency from 1960-1971.  Herman spearheaded large development projects in the Western Addition and the Financial District.

54.name: Serranus Clinton Hastings
54.desc: First Chief Justice of the California Supreme Court, former Attorney General of California, and namesake and dean of the University of California Hastings College of Law.

55.name: George Moscone
55.desc: Mayor of San Francisco from 1976-1978 and a former majority leader of the California State Senate.  During Moscone's term as mayor, he and Supervisor Harvey Milk were shot and killed in San Francisco City Hall by former supervisor Dan White.

57.name: George Davidson
57.desc: An astronomer, engineer, and geographer responsible for many key surveys of the Western United States in the second half of the 19th century.  He was also a charter member of the Sierra Club, president of the California Academy of Sciences from 1871-1877, founder of the first observatory on the Pacific coast, and the first professor of geography at UC Berkeley.

58.name: Victor D. Duboce
58.desc: The colonel in command of the First California Regiment during the Spanish-American War, he served as a member of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors after the war.

59.name: Mission Dolores
59.desc: Created as Mission San Francisco de Asís in 1776, but popularly known as Mission Dolores due to its location near the creek Arroyo de Nuestra Señora de los Dolores, which was so named because it was discovered on the feast day of Our Lady of Sorrows.  It is the oldest surviving building in San Francisco (although the original adobe on the site of the Presidio Officer's Club may predate it).

60.name: Frank H. McCoppin
60.desc: The first foreign-born mayor of San Francisco, serving from 1867-1869.  He also served as supervisor of the Market Street Railway and postmaster of San Francisco.

61.name: Richard Barnes Mason
61.desc: The military governor of California from 1847 to 1849.

62.name: Mark Hopkins
62.desc: One of the "Big Four" co-founders of the Central Pacific Railroad in 1862.  He built a large mansion on the southeastern corner of Nob Hill, which later became the home of the San Francisco Art Association.  After the building was destroyed in the aftermath of the 1906 earthquake, became the site of the current Mark Hopkins Hotel.

63.name: Lillie Hitchcock Coit
63.desc: Famed for her history with San Francisco's volunteer firefighters, Coit became a "mascot" for Knickerbocker Engine Co. No. 5 at the age of fifteen.  She willed one-third of her estate to the city of San Francisco, which used it to construct two monuments: Coit Tower and a statue of firefighters in Washington Square Park.

64.name: José Antonio Yorba
64.desc: A member of Gaspar de Portolà's 1769 expedition into California.

65.name: Juan Rodríguez Cabrillo
65.desc: A Portuguese explorer who became the first European to navigate the California coast in 1542.

66.name: Pedro Benito Cambón
66.desc: A Franciscan friar and member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco. One of the founders of Mission Dolores.

67.name: Donaldina Cameron
67.desc: A New Zealand native and Presbyterian missionary who ran the San Francisco Presbyterian Mission Home for Chinese girls trapped in indentured servitude.

69.name: Juana Cardenas
69.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco along with her husband, Felipe Santiago Tapia.

70.name: Charles D. Carter
70.desc: An early San Francisco settler, real estate agent, and publisher of the San Francisco Real Estate Circular. He also served as President of the Society of Pioneers and on the Board of Industrial School Managers.

71.name: María Gertrudis Castelo
71.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco along with her husband, Juan Atansio Vasquez.

72.name: Pedro de Castenada
72.desc: A historian and member of Francisco Vásquez de Coronado's 1540-1542 expedition into the present-day American Southwest.

73.name: José Antonio Castro
73.desc: The governor of Alta California from 1835-1836 and commander of the Mexican army in Alta California during the Bear Flag Revolt and Mexican-American War.

74.name: Miguel de Cervantes
74.desc: A Spanish novelist and playwright, most famously the author of Don Quixote.

75.name: Cesar Chavez
75.desc: An American farm worker, activist, and labor leader who co-founded the National Farm Workers Association in 1962.  His birthday (March 31) is a state holiday in California.

76.name: Anthony Chabot
76.desc: A mining entrepreneur in 19th-century California who developed of the first hydraulic mining technique and later built San Francisco's first public water system.

77.name: Charles J. Brenham
77.desc: A former riverboat captain who served as mayor of San Francisco in 1851 and again from 1852-1853.

78.name: George Christopher
78.desc: Mayor of San Francisco from 1956-1964.  As of 2013, Christopher was San Francisco's most recent Republican mayor.

79.name: Henry Clay
79.desc: A famous Kentucky orator and politician who served as both US Speaker of the House and US Secretary of State in the early 19th century.

80.name: Charles Clayton
80.desc: A local miner and merchant who served in a variety of public offices in the 19th century, including California state representative, US congressman, member of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors, and customs official for the Port of San Francisco.

81.name: Roswell Clement
81.desc: A San Francisco attorney who served on the Board of Supervisors from 1865-1867.  Some sources claim he had the idea for the westward expansion of Golden Gate Park all the way to the coast.

82.name: Richard Beverly Cole
82.desc: A pioneering San Francisco physician who served as Dean of the University of the Pacific Medical Department from 1858-1864 and later as Dean of the University of California Medical Department.  He also served as Surgeon General of California and president of the American Medical Association, and was instrumental in much of the early development of local hospitals and the area around Golden Gate Park.

83.name: Colin P. Kelly
83.desc: One of the first American military aviators to be killed during World War II.  Kelly was killed on December 10, 1941, during a bombing run in the Philippines.

84.name: Julia Commer
84.desc: A Hunters Point community leader during the 1960s.

85.name: Charles E. Compton
85.desc: The commanding officer of the Presidio in 1899.

86.name: Charles Cora
86.desc: In a famous case from the Commitee of Vigilance years, Cora shot and killed a US Marshal over an insult to his mistress, but after his first trial ended with a hung jury in 1856, he was lynched by an angry mob.

87.name: Hernán Cortés
87.desc: A Spanish conquistador who brought large portions of present-day Mexico under Spanish rule in the 16th century.

88.name: Juan Crespí
88.desc: A Franciscan missionary, author, and member of Gaspar de Portolà's 1769 expedition up the California coast.

89.name: George Custer
89.desc: A US and Union Army commander during the Civil War and the Indian Wars who was famously killed at the Battle of Little Bighorn in 1876.

90.name: Cyril Magnin
90.desc: A prominent San Francisco businessman and Democratic Party power broker, involved in many local cultural and political institutions.  His father Joseph Magnin founded a chain of high-end department stores, which Cyril took over in the mid-20th century.

91.name: Dashiell Hammett
91.desc: The author of popular detective novels, many of them set in San Francisco, where he lived on this street in the 1920s.

92.name: William Heath Davis
92.desc: A prominent San Francisco merchant and shipowner who went on to found New Town San Diego in 1850. His posthumously published book Seventy-Five Years in California serves as an influential account of the pioneer days in the state.

93.name: Francisco De Haro
93.desc: The first alcalde (the equivalent of mayor) of the Mexican settlement of Yerba Buena in 1838.

94.name: George Dewey
94.desc: A naval commander most famous for his victory at the Battle of Manila Bay during the Spanish-American War.  He is the only person ever to achieve the rank of Admiral of the Navy, the most senior rank in the US Navy.

95.name: Peter Donahue
95.desc: A prominent early California industrialist who founded the Union Iron Works in 1849, the San Francisco and San Jose Railroad in 1860, and the Omnibus Street Railroad (San Francisco's first streetcar) in 1861.

96.name: John G. Downey
96.desc: Governor of California from 1860-1862.  Downey was immensely popular in San Francisco owing to his veto of the "Bulkhead Bill," a bill that would have put the San Francisco waterfront under private monopoly ownership.  Downey was born in Ireland, making him the state's only foreign-born governor prior to Arnold Schwarzenegger.

97.name: Frank Pierce Doyle
97.desc: A Santa Rosa banker known as the "father of the Golden Gate Bridge." He organized the first meeting of the Bridging the Golden Gate Association, and led the efforts for the passage of the $35 million bond issue for the bridge's construction and the creation of the Golden Gate Bridge Highway and Transportation District.

98.name: Carlton P. Goodlett
98.desc: A local physician and civil rights leader who founded the Sun-Reporter newsweekly and ran for governor of California in 1966.

99.name: Sir Francis Drake
99.desc: An English explorer and privateer who circumnavigated the globe from 1577-1580.  He landed on the coast of Northern California in 1579 and claimed it for the English Crown under the name Nova Albion (Latin for "New Britain").

100.name: Harry C. Egbert
100.desc: A Union and US Army commander who was killed during the Philippine-American War in 1899.

101.name: Levi Richard Ellert
101.desc: Mayor of San Francisco from 1893-1895, the first San Francisco native to serve as mayor.

102.name: Alfred J. Ellis
102.desc: Hotel owner and a delegate to the California Constitutional Convention in 1849.

103.name: Espanola Jackson
103.desc: A Hunters Point community leader during the 1960s.

104.name: Robley D. Evans
104.desc: A US Navy commander who led Theodore Roosevelt's "Great White Fleet" into San Francisco Bay in 1908.

105.name: James Graham Fair
105.desc: A real estate and railroad speculator who made his fortune as one of the four part-owners of the Comstock Lode known as the "Bonanza Kings" and later served as a US senator from Nevada.  The San Francisco Fairmont Hotel is located on his former land and named for him.

106.name: Charles S. Fairfax
106.desc: A Virginia-born Scottish nobleman who moved to San Francisco in 1850 during the height of the Gold Rush.  He later went into state politics, serving as Speaker of the Assembly in 1854 and Clerk of the California Supreme Court from 1856-1861.  The town of Fairfax in Marin County is also named for him.

107.name: David Farragut
107.desc: A long-serving US Navy officer who began as a midshipman during the War of 1812 at the age of nine and commanded the Union Navy during the Civil War.  He is locally known for establishing the Mare Island Naval Shipyard in 1854, the first US naval base on the Pacific Ocean.

108.name: Charles N. Felton
108.desc: A local merchant who served in a variety of public offices during the second half of the 19th century, including treasurer of the San Francisco Mint, state assemblyman, and US senator from California.

109.name: Millard Fillmore
109.desc: President of the United States from 1850-1853.  He officially admitted California as a state on September 9, 1850.

110.name: George Kenyon Fitch
110.desc: A 19th-century San Francisco newspaperman who owned the San Francisco Bulletin, the Daily Morning Call, and the Daily Alta California.

111.name: James Clair Flood
111.desc: A stock speculator and one of the four part-owners of the Comstock Lode known as the "Bonanza Kings."  He also built the Flood Mansion on Nob Hill, now the home of the Pacific-Union Club.

112.name: Joseph L. Folsom
112.desc: A soldier and California real estate investor who founded Granite City on the American River in 1854, later renamed Folsom in his honor.

113.name: Pedro Font
113.desc: A chaplain and diarist with Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

114.name: Henry B. Freeman
114.desc: Recipient of the Medal of Honor during the Civil War and commander of the Presidio in 1899.

115.name: John C. Fremont
115.desc: An American military officer, explorer, and politician nicknamed "The Pathfinder."  He led several expeditions into present-day California beginning in 1842, becoming the first American to see Lake Tahoe.  He also took command of the Bear Flag Republic for the United States in 1846, and went on to become one of the first two US senators from California and the first Republican Party candidate for president.

116.name: Frederick Funston
116.desc: Commander of the Presidio when the 1906 earthquake struck San Francisco, he used the military to impose law and order in the aftermath of the earthquake and ordered targeted demolitions to stop the spread of fires, most notably along Van Ness Avenue.

117.name: José de Gálvez
117.desc: The Spanish Visitor General who dispatched Gaspar de Portolà's expedition up the California coast in 1769.

118.name: Francisco Garcés
118.desc: A Franciscan friar and missionary who accompanied Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition toward San Francisco.

119.name: Ethel Garlington
119.desc: A Hunters Point community leader during the 1960s.

120.name: C.K. Garrison
120.desc: A shipbuilder and businessman who became the fourth mayor of San Francisco in 1853.

121.name: John W. Geary
121.desc: The last alcalde and first mayor of San Francisco, elected in 1850.  He went on to serve as governor of the Kansas Territory and later as governor of Pennsylvania.  He also served with distinction as an officer in both the Mexican-American and Civil Wars.

122.name: Edward Gilbert
122.desc: A printer who arrived in San Francisco during service in the Mexican-American War and went on to become editor of the Daily Alta California newspaper. He was also the youngest delegate to the California Constitutional Convention in 1849. Gilbert was later killed in a duel with General James Denver, the future namesake of the Colorado city, after publishing an article accusing Denver of negligence and mismanagement during an aid expedition.

123.name: Daniel Coit Gilman
123.desc: Became the third president of the University of Calfornia in 1872 after serving as the first president of Johns Hopkins University.  He is credited with introducing German-style graduate education to American universities.

124.name: Johann Wolfgang von Goethe
124.desc: A German author and poet most famous for the play Faust, published in 1808.

125.name: José Manuel Gonzales
125.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

126.name: George Gordon
126.desc: A native Londoner who was instrumental in developing the South Park neighborhood of San Francisco.  He also founded San Francisco's first immigration society and first sugar refinery.

127.name: Charles H. Gough
127.desc: A local milkman who served on the 1855 committee tasked with naming the streets of the Western Addition. He named Gough Street after himself and Octavia Street after his sister, and may have named Steiner Street after a friend.

128.name: Ulysses S. Grant
128.desc: The commanding general of the Union Army during the Civil War and President of the United States from 1869-1877.

129.name: Talbot H. Green
129.desc: Talbot H. Green arrived in California in 1841 and became a wealthy local businessman, but in 1850-1851 it came out that he was actually Paul Geddes, a man wanted for embezzlement in Pennsylvania who had abandoned his wife and children there. He fled the city under false pretenses, later returning to San Francisco and then Pennsylvania much later and repaying his debts with the help of his friend Thomas Larkin.

130.name: Millen Griffith
130.desc: An early San Francisco businessman and partner in the Pacific Steam Whaling Company.

131.name: Juan Pablo Grijalva
131.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

132.name: Francisco Guerrero
132.desc: A local landowner who served as alcalde (the equivalent of mayor) of Yerba Buena before the Mexican-American War. He was murdered at the corner of 12th Street & Mission Street in 1851, allegedly by a man on horseback with a slingshot. He was scheduled as a witness in a high-profile fraud case and the killing may have been to silence his testimony.

133.name: Francisco de Ulloa
133.desc: A Spanish explorer who navigated much of the west coast of present-day Mexico beginning in 1539.

134.name: Gonzalo Jiménez de Quesada
134.desc: A 16th-century Spanish conquistador and explorer of South America.  Because of his failed search for El Dorado, the "Lost City of Gold," some suggest he is the model for the character of Don Quixote.

135.name: Rufus Ingalls
135.desc: A US Army soldier in the New Mexico Territory during the Mexican-American War and later a general in the Union Army during the Civil War.  He became the 16th Quartermaster General of the US Army in 1882.

136.name: Washington Irving
136.desc: An early American author and essayist, one of the first to earn international popularity, most famous for his short stories "Rip Van Winkle" and "The Legend of Sleepy Hollow."

137.name: Henry Haight
137.desc: An early San Francisco pioneer and manager of the Page, Bacon, & Co. banking company during the Gold Rush era.  Not to be confused with his nephew Henry Huntly Haight, governor of California from 1867-1871.

138.name: Henry W. Halleck
138.desc: A US Army engineer who constructed fortifications in California during the Mexican-American War and became military secretary of state to California beginning in 1847, serving as the military governor's representative at the California Constitutional Convention in 1849.  He assembled a large collection of California historical documents, copies of which now reside in the Bancroft Library at UC Berkeley.

139.name: James Allen Hardie
139.desc: The first American commander of the Presidio, serving from 1847-1849.

140.name: Warren G. Harding
140.desc: President of the United States from 1921-1923, he died suddenly at the Palace Hotel in San Francisco in 1923 while still in office.

141.name: Charles Harney
141.desc: A local real estate developer in the mid-20th century, most notable for his controversial involvement in the construction of Candlestick Park in 1958.  Harney made a conspicuous profit on the sale of quarry land for the stadium site and then received a no-bid contract to build it, which became the subject of a grand jury investigation.

142.name: Stephen Randall Harris
142.desc: A physician and gold prospector who served as San Francisco's third mayor in 1852.

143.name: Edward H. Harrison
143.desc: A local merchant who served on the Town Council and as collector for the city port in early San Francisco during the Gold Rush era.

144.name: Horace Hawes
144.desc: A prominent attorney during the Gold Rush era who served in the California State Assembly and State Senate.  Prior to 1856, San Francisco County included the City of San Francisco as well as land to the south; Hawes was responsible for splitting it into the City-County of San Francisco and San Mateo County to the south.

145.name: Thomas Hayes
145.desc: A local landowner and investor who also served as county clerk from 1853 to 1856.  His brother Michael served on the committee responsible for naming the new streets of the Western Addition in 1855.

146.name: George Hearst
146.desc: A Gold Rush prospector who grew wealthy from silver found in the Comstock Lode. He purchased the San Francisco Examiner, which was later passed to his son William Randolph Hearst. The elder Hearst also served as a US senator from 1887-1891.

147.name: Herman and Maurice Herbst
147.desc: Brothers who ran a sheet metal shop on Mission Street during the 1930s and began investing in San Francisco real estate.  They established a foundation that benefits many local landmarks, including the Herbst Theater and the San Francisco Zoo.

148.name: Ygnacio Anastacio Higuera
148.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

149.name: William Davis Merry Howard
149.desc: A sailor and early settler who served on San Francisco's first city council.  He was also involved in the formation of the Committee of Vigilance in 1851.

150.name: Victor Hugo
150.desc: A 19th-century French novelist and poet, famous for works such as Les Misérables and The Hunchback of Notre-Dame.

151.name: Alexander von Humboldt
151.desc: An influential German naturalist and explorer who undertook an expedition to Latin America from 1799-1804 and later published the Kosmos, a treatise that attempted to unify known scientific principles.

152.name: Collis Potter Huntington
152.desc: A railroad magnate and member of the "Big Four" responsible for the Central Pacific Railroad.  The Huntington Hotel on Nob Hill is also named for him.

153.name: George Hyde
153.desc: A captain's clerk in the US Navy who became the third alcalde (the equivalent of mayor) of San Francisco after Washington A. Bartlett and Edwin Bryant.

154.name: William T. Wallace
154.desc: Attorney General of California from 1856 to 1858 and Chief Justice of the California Supreme Court from 1870-1879.

155.name: R.H. Waller
155.desc: City recorder during the 1850s and a manager of the San Francisco Protestant Orphan Asylum on Haight Street.

156.name: Walter U. Lum
156.desc: A Chinese-American activist in the early 20th century. He founded the Chinese Times newspaper, fought for the repeal of the Chinese Exclusion Act, and ran a school for Chinese-American children.

157.name: George Washington
157.desc: One of the Founding Fathers, commander of the Continental Army during the Revolutionary War, and first President of the United States.

158.name: Elouise Westbrooke
158.desc: A Hunters Point community leader during the 1960s.

159.name: Amiel W. Whipple
159.desc: A military engineer and surveyor who led explorations for the first transcontinental railroad route.  He was killed at the Battle of Chancellorsville while fighting for the Union Army during the Civil War.

160.name: Whitney Young
160.desc: An American civil rights leader who headed the National Urban League from 1961-1971.

161.name: Willie B. Kennedy
161.desc: A member of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors from 1981-1996, later a member of the BART Board of Directors.

163.name: George Wright
163.desc: Commander of the Department of the Pacific for the Union Army during the Civil War.

164.name: Mariano Guadalupe Vallejo
164.desc: A wealthy landowner and commander of the Presidio under Mexican rule in the 1830s and later a key figure in the transition from Mexican to American rule.  During the Bear Flag Revolt, the flag was first raised on the grounds of Vallejo's estate.  He served as a delegate to the California Constitutional Convention in 1849.

165.name: Martin Van Buren
165.desc: President of the United States from 1837-1841 and one of the organizers of the Democratic Party.

166.name: Walter Van Dyke
166.desc: A California Supreme Court justice from 1891-1905.

168.name: Casimiro Varela
168.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

169.name: Mariano Vidal
169.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

170.name: Jasper O'Farrell
170.desc: A civil engineer who completed a key survey of San Francisco in 1847 that determined much of the modern street layout, including the diagonal boulevard of Market Street.  O'Farrell is believed to have named several streets, including Market, Sansome, and Filbert Streets, after streets in Philadelphia, where he had previously lived.

171.name: Michael O'Shaugnessy
171.desc: A civil engineer responsible for many projects in California and Hawaii in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.  He served as San Francisco's chief engineer from 1912-1934, during which time he oversaw the construction of the Municipal Railway System, the Stockton Street Tunnel, and the Twin Peaks Tunnel.  He was also responsible for the controversial Hetch Hetchy reservoir project, which dammed the Hetch Hetchy Valley in Yosemite National Park and built a pipeline to supply its water to San Francisco.

172.name: Ora Robinson
172.desc: The wife of Elmer Robinson, mayor of San Francisco from 1948-1956.

173.name: Edward Ord
173.desc: A military engineer stationed in California beginning in 1847.  He planned a large portion of the Sacramento street grid and completed a key survey of the pueblo of Los Angeles.

174.name: José Francisco Ortega
174.desc: Chief scout of Gaspar de Portolà's 1769 expedition up the California coast, possibly the first member to see San Francisco Bay.

175.name: Osceola Washington
175.desc: A Hunters Point community leader during the 1960s.

176.name: James Otis
176.desc: A Boston native who became the mayor of San Francisco from 1873 until his death in 1875. He is the only San Francisco mayor other than George Moscone to die in office.

177.name: Jack Kerouac
177.desc: An influential beat writer and poet who lived in North Beach during the San Francisco Renaissance of the 1940s and 1950s.

178.name: Jack London
178.desc: An American author, mariner, and San Francisco native who attended UC Berkeley and later lived in Oakland. He is most famous for the novels The Call of the Wild and White Fang, both set during the Klondike Gold Rush.

179.name: Andrew Jackson
179.desc: President of the United States from 1829-1837.

180.name: James Lick
180.desc: A carpenter by training and early San Francisco settler who acquired large land holdings throughout California during the Gold Rush which made him, by some estimates, the wealthiest man in California at the time of his death.  He funded the construction of several monuments and public works throughout San Francisco as well as the Lick Observatory in San Jose, which contained the most powerful telescope in the world at the time of its construction.

181.name: Thomas Jefferson
181.desc: One of the Founding Fathers, author of the Declaration of Independence, and President of the United States from 1801-1809.

182.name: John F. Kennedy
182.desc: President of the United States from 1961 until his assassination in 1963.

183.name: John F. Shelley
183.desc: Mayor of San Francisco from 1964 to 1968, the city's first Democratic mayor in 50 years.  As of 2013, every San Francisco mayor since Shelley has been a Democrat.

184.name: John Muir
184.desc: A prominent naturalist, conservationist, and founder of the Sierra Club.  He wrote many books about his time in the wilderness, particularly the Sierra Nevada mountains, and fought to preserve California forests from developments such as the Hetch Hetchy Reservoir.

185.name: Behrend Joost
185.desc: A local merchant who arrived in San Francisco in 1857 and later built the first electric railway going south from downtown San Francisco, connecting it to portions of San Mateo County and neighborhoods like Glen Park (where Joost Street is located).

186.name: Theodore Judah
186.desc: The chief engineer for the Central Pacific Railroad who surveyed the route over the Sierra Nevada mountains for the completion of the Transcontinental Railroad.

187.name: Junipero Serra
187.desc: A Franciscan friar who established the first Spanish mission in Alta California and led the establishment of missions up the California coast.

188.name: Stephen W. Kearny
188.desc: A US Army commander during the Mexican-American War who played a key role in the conquest of California and served as military governor of the territory in 1847.

190.name: Ralph W. Kirkham
190.desc: A US Army soldier in the Mexican-American War who later became quartermaster of the Presidio and a prominent Oakland businessman.

191.name: Tandang Sora
191.desc: The nickname for Melchora Aquino, a Filipina woman who aided the revolutionaries during the Philippine Revolution against the Spanish in 1896.

192.name: Felipe Santiago Tapia
192.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

193.name: Sebastian Taraval
193.desc: A Native American guide for Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

194.name: Zachary Taylor
194.desc: A US Army commander during the Mexican-American War and President of the United States from 1849-1850.

195.name: Terry A. Francois
195.desc: A civil rights activist and the first African-American member of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors, serving from 1964-1978.

196.name: George Henry Thomas
196.desc: A US and Union Army commander who served in the Mexican-American and Civil Wars and became commander of the Presidio from 1869 until his death in 1870.

197.name: Hugh Huger Toland
197.desc: A prominent local surgeon who founded Toland Medical College, which became UCSF Medical School in 1873.

198.name: James Townsend
198.desc: A local physician who served as alcalde (the equivalent of mayor) of San Francisco in 1848.

199.name: Frank Turk
199.desc: A local attorney who served as a deputy mayor of San Francisco under John W. Geary in 1850.

200.name: Levi Cooper Lane
200.desc: A local physician who founded Cooper Medical College, which became the Stanford Medical Department in 1908.

201.name: Roger Lapham
201.desc: Mayor of San Francisco from 1944-1948.  He became the subject of the first mayoral recall election in San Francisco history after he increased streetcar fares (the recall effort failed).

202.name: Lapu Lapu
202.desc: An early Filipino hero who resisted Spanish colonization and led one side in the 1521 Battle of Mactan, during which Ferdinand Magellan was killed.

203.name: Thomas O. Larkin
203.desc: An early settler who arrived in San Francisco in 1832 during Mexican rule.  He was appointed by President John Tyler as the first (and only) US consul to Alta California and served as a clandestine US agent during the Bear Flag Revolt.  He later served as a delegate to the California Constitutional Convention in 1849.

204.name: Henry Ware Lawton
204.desc: A US and Union Army commander who served in the Civil War, Spanish-American War, and Philippine-American War.  He was killed during the Battle of Paye in 1899, the highest-ranking officer to be killed during the Philippine-American War.

205.name: Lech Wałęsa
205.desc: A Polish labor activist and leader of the Solidarity movement who was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1983 and became president of Poland in 1990.

206.name: John Le Conte
206.desc: A scientist and academic who served as the president of the University of California from 1869-1870 and again from 1875-1881.

207.name: Thaddeus M. Leavenworth
207.desc: The alcalde (the equivalent of mayor) of San Francisco from 1848-1849.

208.name: Jacob P. Leese
208.desc: An early pioneer who built the first permanent house in Yerba Buena near the present-day corner of Grant Avenue and Clay Street. He was taken captive at Sutter's Fort during the Bear Flag Revolt of 1846. Leese is the brother-in-law of Mariano Guadalupe Vallejo.

209.name: John Lendrum
209.desc: Commander of the Presidio in 1858 and of Fort Point in 1861.

210.name: Hunter Liggett
210.desc: Commander of the US First Army during World War I.  He is buried in the Presidio.

211.name: Ygnacio Antonio Linares
211.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

212.name: Abraham Lincoln
212.desc: President of the United States and leader of the Union during the Civil War, in office from 1861 until his assassination in 1865.

213.name: Nathaniel Lyon
213.desc: A US Army commander in the Mexican-American War who became the first Union army general to be killed in the Civil War in 1861.

214.name: John B. Montgomery
214.desc: A US Navy officer who arrived in San Francisco Bay in 1846 in command of the USS Portsmouth and was drawn into the Bear Flag Revolt. He led the detachment that first raised the American flag in Yerba Buena that same year and later commanded the Pacific Squadron of the US Navy from 1859-1862.

215.name: Nancy Pelosi
215.desc: A congresswoman who has represented San Francisco since 1987, becoming the first female Speaker of the House in 2007.

216.name: Simon Newcomb
216.desc: A 19th-century astronomer and mathematician who contributed to the science of planetary motion and timekeeping.

217.name: Henry M. Newhall
217.desc: Founder of the H.M. Newhall & Company auction house in San Francisco during the Gold Rush.  He went on to become a wealthy railroad and real estate investor, owning large tracts in Central and Southern California.

218.name: Chester Nimitz
218.desc: Commander of the US Navy's Pacific Fleet during World War II.  He moved to the San Francisco Bay Area after the war and served as a Regent of the University of California from 1948-1956.  Interstate 880 (the Nimitz Freeway) is also named for him.

219.name: José de Jesús Noé
219.desc: The last Mexican alcalde (the equivalent of mayor) of Yerba Buena before it was claimed by the United States in 1846 during the Mexican-American War.

220.name: José de la Guerra y Noriega
220.desc: A Spanish military officer who became commander of the Presidio of Santa Barbara from 1827-1842.

221.name: Apolinario Mabini
221.desc: A Filipino philosopher and revolutionary who served as the first Prime Minister of the Philippines in 1899.

222.name: Arthur MacArthur, Jr.
222.desc: A US Army commander who became the military Governor-General of the Philippines during American occupation in 1900.  He was also the father of five-star general Douglas MacArthur.

223.name: James Madison
223.desc: One of the Founding Fathers, a principal author of the United States Consitution and Bill of Rights, and President of the United States from 1809-1817.

224.name: Charles Main
224.desc: An early settler and businessman who served as director of the San Francisco Central Railroad.

225.name: Martin Luther King, Jr.
225.desc: A prominent civil rights leader in the 1950s and 1960s and founder of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference.  He received the Nobel Peace Prize in 1964.

226.name: Matthew Hall McAllister
226.desc: A prominent local attorney during the Gold Rush era who became a US Circuit Court judge in 1855.

227.name: John McLaren
227.desc: A Scottish horticulturalist who served as superintendent of Golden Gate Park for 53 years, from 1887-1940.

228.name: George Meade
228.desc: A US and Union Army general best known for defeating the Confederate Army at the Battle of Gettysburg in 1863.

229.name: George H. Mendell
229.desc: An engineer in the US Army who supervised the construction of many of the military fortifications around San Francisco Bay in the late 19th century.

230.name: Antonio de Mendoza
230.desc: The Viceroy of New Spain from 1535-1550 who commissioned the Cabrillo and Coronado expeditions into Alta California.

231.name: Charles S. Merchant
231.desc: A US Army officer who served as commander of the Presidio in 1861.

232.name: John D. Miley
232.desc: A US Army officer who served in the Spanish-American War and was killed in the Philippines in 1899.  Fort Miley, the grounds of which now contain San Francisco's VA Medical Center, was also named for him.

233.name: Fernando Rivera y Moncada
233.desc: The leader of a 1769 expedition into Alta California and military governor of California from 1774-1777.

234.name: Garci Rodríguez de Montalvo
234.desc: Author of the 16th-century novel Las Sergas de Esplandián, the novel from which the name California is likely derived. The novel describes an island paradise inhabited by woman warriors and named for their queen, Calafia.

235.name: Montezuma II
235.desc: The last ruler of the Aztec empire in present-day Mexico before its conquest by Hernán Cortés and the Spanish in the early 16th century.

236.name: José Joaquín Moraga
236.desc: Second-in-command on Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco, and the founder of the pueblo that became the city of San Jose.

237.name: J. Mora Moss
237.desc: A prominent local businessman who arrived in San Francisco in the early 1850s, became the first president of the San Francisco Gas Company, and later served as a Regent of the University of California.

238.name: Juan Salvio Pacheco
238.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

239.name: Francisco Palóu
239.desc: A Franciscan missionary who played a key role in the establishment of California's Spanish mission system. He was also a member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

240.name: Gabriel Peralta
240.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

241.name: John J. Pershing
241.desc: Commander of US forces during World War I, and the only person besides George Washington to hold the rank of General of the Armies of the United States.

242.name: Peter Yorke
242.desc: A Catholic priest and labor activist in San Francisco dring the early 20th century.

243.name: James Phelan
243.desc: An early San Francisco settler who became a wealthy businessman and established the First National Gold Bank of San Francisco.  He was the father of James D. Phelan, who served as mayor of San Francisco from 1897-1902 and as a US senator from California from 1915-1921.

244.name: Timothy Guy Phelps
244.desc: A wealthy San Francisco businessman and real estate investor who served as the first president of the Southern Pacific Railroad from 1865-1868.

245.name: Pío Pico
245.desc: The last governor of Alta California under Mexican rule, serving from 1845-1846 before American occupation during the Mexican-American War.

246.name: Franklin Pierce
246.desc: A Brigadier General in the Mexican-American War who became President of the United States from 1853-1857.

247.name: Pablo Pinto
247.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

248.name: François Pioche
248.desc: A prominent San Francisco financier and real estate developer during the Gold Rush era.

249.name: Frank M. Pixley
249.desc: City Attorney of San Francisco who later served as Attorney General of California from 1860 to 1861. He founded the influential literary journal The Argonaut in 1877.

250.name: Francisco Pizarro
250.desc: A Spanish conquistador and explorer who conquered the Inca Empire in present-day Peru.

251.name: Mary Ellen Pleasant
251.desc: A San Francisco civil rights activist and abolitionist during the middle of the 19th century.

252.name: James K. Polk
252.desc: President of the United States from 1845-1849.  He led the US to victory in the Mexican-American War, during which California passed from Mexican to American control.

254.name: Gaspar de Portolà
254.desc: A Spanish explorer who led an expedition through Alta California to San Francisco Bay in 1769.

255.name: William Chapman Ralston
255.desc: An early San Francisco financier who built the Palace Hotel and founded the Bank of California before losing his fortune in the financial crisis of 1873.

256.name: Ira P. Rankin
256.desc: A local merchant who arrived in San Francisco in 1852 and went on to serve as the local port collector and president of the Chamber of Commerce.

257.name: Paul Revere
257.desc: An American revolutionary and folk hero most famous for his "midnight ride" warning colonial troops before the Battles of Lexington and Concord, the subject of a poem by Henry Wadsworth Longfellow.

258.name: William A. Richardson
258.desc: An early settler who served as port captain of Yerba Buena and received large land grants around San Francisco Bay, one of which became the city of Sausalito.

259.name: Bennet C. Riley
259.desc: A US Army commander during the Mexican-American War and the last military governor of California prior to statehood, serving from 1849-1850.

260.name: Cadwalader Ringgold
260.desc: A US Navy officer who participated in the first US expedition into the Pacific Ocean in 1838 and completed key surveys of San Francisco Bay and surrounding waterways.

261.name: Maria Gertrudis Rivas
261.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

262.name: José Rizal
262.desc: A Filipino revolutionary and national hero who was executed by the Spanish for sedition in 1896.

263.name: Phillip A. Roach
263.desc: The first mayor of Monterey after California transferred to American control, and later a San Francisco port and administration official.

264.name: Elmer Robinson
264.desc: Mayor of San Francisco from 1948-1956. Ora Street is named after his wife.

265.name: James Rolph, Jr.
265.desc: The longest-serving mayor in San Francisco history, in office from 1912-1931.  He resigned as mayor to become the governor of California from 1931-1934.

266.name: Rosa Parks
266.desc: A civil rights icon most famous for her role in the Montgomery Bus Boycott of 1955-56.

267.name: Angelo Joseph Rossi
267.desc: Mayor of San Francisco from 1931-1944, he was in office during the construction of both the Golden Gate and Bay Bridges.

268.name: John W. Ruckman
268.desc: A US Army officer who served as commander of Fort Baker (located near Sausalito) from 1909-1910.

269.name: Charles Christian Russ
269.desc: A local merchant who became wealthy during the Gold Rush era and built the American Hotel on Montgomery Street. The hotel has since been replaced by the Russ Building, a gothic skyscraper that was San Francisco's tallest building from 1927-1964.

270.name: José Antonio Sánchez
270.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco who went on to serve as a soldier in the Presidio and receive a large land grant in present-day San Mateo County.

271.name: Winfield Scott
271.desc: A US Army general during the War of 1812, the Mexican-American War, and the Civil War.  The longest-serving general in US history (47 years) and the longest-serving Commanding General of the United States Army (20 years).

272.name: Thomas Henry Selby
272.desc: A local merchant who served as mayor of San Francisco from 1869-1871.

273.name: Ana Regina Serrano
273.desc: Juan Bautista de Anza's wife, and a member of his 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

274.name: William H. Seward
274.desc: US Secretary of State from 1861-1869 under Presidents Lincoln and Johnson, most famous for negotiating the purchase of Alaska from Russia.  He also served as Governor of New York and a US senator from New York.

275.name: William Rufus Shafter
275.desc: US Army officer who served as commander of the Department of California both before and after the Spanish-American War in addition to his service during the war.  Earlier received the Medal of Honor for his service in the Union Army during the Civil War.

276.name: William Shakespeare
276.desc: Considered one of the greatest English-language playwrights and poets of all time.  Produced 38 plays as well as other poems and sonnets in the late 16th and early 17th centuries.

277.name: William Sharon
277.desc: A wealthy businessman who served as a US senator from Nevada from 1875-1881.

278.name: William Tecumseh Sherman
278.desc: A Union Army commander during the Civil War most famous for burning Atlanta and his March to the Sea.  He earlier served in the Mexican-American War and worked as a San Francisco bank manager during the Gold Rush.

279.name: A.I. Shrader
279.desc: A member of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors from 1865-1872 who was involved in the establishment of Golden Gate Park in 1870.

280.name: George S. Simonds
280.desc: A US Army officer who served as commander of the Presidio from 1936-1938.

281.name: John D. Sloat
281.desc: A US Navy Commodore who captured Monterey from Mexico in 1846 and briefly served as the first military governor of California under American rule.

282.name: Pablo Vicente de Solá
282.desc: The last governor of Alta California under Spanish rule, from 1815-1822.

283.name: José Antonio Sotelo
283.desc: A member of Juan Bautista de Anza's 1775-1776 expedition to San Francisco.

284.name: William Sproul
284.desc: The president of Southern Pacific Railroad beginning in 1911.

285.name: Leland Stanford
285.desc: Stanford moved to San Francisco in 1852 and became the first president of Central Pacific Railroad and one of its "Big Four" founders.  He also served as a US senator from California and Governor of California, and presided over the driving of the "Golden Spike" in Promontory, Utah, completing the Transcontinental Railroad.  He later founded Stanford University, which opened in 1891.

286.name: C.H. Stanyan
286.desc: A member of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors  involved in the establishment of Golden Gate Park in 1870.

287.name: Thomas Starr King
287.desc: A minister, orator, and prominent Unionist in the run-up to the Civil War, credited by President Lincoln with keeping California in the Union.

288.name: William M. Steuart
288.desc: Member of the San Francisco town council in 1849 and a delegate to the California Constitutional Convention in 1849.

289.name: Robert F. Stockton
289.desc: A US Navy Commodore who commanded the US forces in California during the Mexican-American War and brought it under American control.  The California city of Stockton is also named for him.

290.name: John Sutter
290.desc: Born Johann August Suter in Switzerland, Sutter arrived in San Francisco in 1839.  He is best known as the owner of Sutter's Mill, the site on the American River where gold was discovered in 1848, kicking off the California Gold Rush.

291.name: William Leidesdorff
291.desc: One of the first mixed-race citizens of California, Leidesdorff was born in the West Indies and arrived in San Francisco in 1841.  He became a successful businessman, built the first hotel in the city, and served on the town council.  He later donated a parcel of land to build the first public school in California and piloted the first steamboat up the Sacramento River (some sources claim this is the steamboat depicted on the California State Seal).  He was appointed US Vice Consul to Mexico in 1845, making him the first African-American diplomat in US history.

293.name: Thomas Butler King
293.desc: A state senator and US representative from Georgia who became San Francisco Port Collector in 1850 and went on to work as a lobbyist for Southern Pacific Railroad.

294.name: Louis Juri
294.desc: A Swiss-born farmer and dairyman during the pioneer era who deeded land near the present-day corner of 25th Street and San Jose Avenue for the construction of the San Francisco-San Jose Railroad.

295.name: William Pfeiffer
295.desc: A German immigrant who built a large brick mansion in present-day Telegraph Hill in 1859.  The construction of the home bankrupted him and he was forced to move his family into a makeshift home in the alley next door.

296.name: William M. Eddy
296.desc: Elected as City Surveyor of San Francisco in 1849 and California Surveyor General in 1851.

297.name: William Keith
297.desc: A Scottish-American artist and friend of John Muir who settled in San Francisco in 1859 and later became known for his paintings of California landscapes.

Bernal Heights.name: Bernal Heights
Bernal Heights.history: Bernal Heights/Bernal Hill is presumably named after José Cornelio Bernal, but may have been named after his grandfather, Anza expedition member Juan Francisco Bernal.

Cole Valley.name: Cole Valley
Cole Valley.history: Cole Street is likely named after physician Richard Beverly Cole.

Dogpatch.name: Dogpatch
Dogpatch.history: Originally part of the Nuevo Potrero pasture, this neighborhood became an industrial center in the second half of the 19th century and home to the immigrant enclaves Irish Hill and Dutchman's Flat.  The origin of the name is unclear, but may refer to a proliferation of dogs scavenging from nearby slaughterhouses.

Glen Park.name: Glen Park
Glen Park.history: Named for Glen Canyon Park, the name of which may simply refer to its location in a narrow valley (or "glen"). Adolph Sutro purchased the park's land in the 1850's and named it Gum Tree Ranch after the newly planted eucalyptus trees. In 1867-68, the land was leased by the Giant Powder Company and became the site of the first commercial dynamite manufacturing operation in the United States; the site was destroyed in an explosion in 1869 and rebuilt in the present-day Outer Sunset.

Haight.name: Haight
Haight.history: Haight Street is presumably named after the banker Henry Haight, but this is uncertain. There were two other Haight brothers in San Francisco in the early 1850's, Fletcher and Samuel Haight, and Fletcher's son Henry Huntly Haight went on to become governor of California.

Hayes Valley.name: Hayes Valley
Hayes Valley.history: Hayes Street is presumably named after local businessman Thomas Hayes, but may also refer to his brother Michael and the rest of the Hayes family.

Inner Richmond.name: Inner Richmond
Inner Richmond.history: Named for the Richmond House, a house built by early settler George Turner Marsh near the present-day corner of 12th Avenue & Clement Street. Marsh was an Australian who named the house after his hometown of Richmond, a suburb of Melbourne. From 1917-2009, the Richmond District was officially known as the Park-Presidio District to avoid confusion with the East Bay city of Richmond.

Mission.name: Mission
Mission.history: Mission Street, the longest street in San Francisco, is named for its path along the original mission trail, which connected Mission Dolores and the village of Yerba Buena.

Nob Hill.name: Nob Hill
Nob Hill.history: Because of its prime location, this neighborhood has been home to some of the wealthiest San Francisco residents throughout the city's history.  One story claims it got its name from the slang term "nob" for a wealthy person, derived from either "nobility" or "nabob."

Outer Richmond.name: Outer Richmond
Outer Richmond.history: Named for the Richmond House, a house built by early settler George Turner Marsh near the present-day corner of 12th Avenue & Clement Street. Marsh was an Australian who named the house after his hometown of Richmond, a suburb of Melbourne. From 1917-2009, the Richmond District was officially known as the Park-Presidio District to avoid confusion with the East Bay city of Richmond.

Potrero Hill.name: Potrero Hill
Potrero Hill.history: Spanish missionaries originally used this hill as grazing land for cattle, calling it Nuevo Potrero (Spanish for "new pasture").

Presidio.name: Presidio
Presidio.history: This base was first built by the Spanish in 1776 ("presidio" is a Spanish word for an early military fortification).  It was taken over by the US during the Mexican-American War in 1846 and in continuous service until being decommissioned and transferred to the National Park Service in 1994.

Russian Hill.name: Russian Hill
Russian Hill.history: One story claims that this neighborhood got its name from the discovery of an early Russian cemetery on this hill during the Gold Rush era.

Tenderloin.name: Tenderloin
Tenderloin.history: There are numerous theories for the origin of this neighborhood's name, one of the most popular being that police officers working in the district in its early years received extra hazard pay, and so could afford the more expensive cut of meat.

Western Addition.name: Western Addition
Western Addition.history: This name comes from the expansion of city boundaries west of Larkin Street to include this land. Many of the streets in the new area got their names from an 1855 naming committee that included Thomas H. Gough.
